Czech Discovery: a substance that also works on 'hardened' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new compounds that can slow down the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already gained immunity against medicines.
This fact in some cases outweighs the fact that the compound does not act as strongly on the normal variant of the virus as some of the medicines already available.
AIDS disease cannot yet be cured.
However, a mixture of medicines that prevent the proliferation of HIV in the body may significantly prolong patients' lives.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, the incomplete suppression of virus multiplication results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from the University of Heidelberg Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarborans act on proteins responsible for the multiplication of HIV.
Metalocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all the drugs used today, so they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists come up with new "enhanced' compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viral protein.
Metal carboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by an atom of metal, in this case with cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is an HIV protein that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by HIV fragmentation, there would be no mature infectious viral particles.
If we stop HIV protease, we stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see the table) are linked to a short organic chain, which is further systematically altered.
A little weaker but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease has been tested in the test tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metallocarborans on the normal variant of the enzyme is not as strong as that of the medicines used, but does not lose its effect on resistant variants against which the medicines used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and their other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical treatments from metallocarborans make interesting compounds for further research towards the design of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
