75% of working mothers have maternity-related work problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially in younger women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the 'Fertility and Work Career of Spanish Women' study conducted by the CSIC in cooperation with the Institute of Women.
The study was attended by 9.737 women aged between 15 and 75 years, and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities on the labour market due to motherhood.
The study stresses that at the beginning of the partnership there are many differences in opinion on the number of children depending on whether they work or not, as well as on the type of employment.
Women who do not work away from home, work part-time, or have a stable job, start living with their partner sooner, have a first child before, and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, postpone cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women from 35 to 49 years of age with stable employment have the first child on average 3.7 years from the beginning of cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 in the case of women who have devoted more of their lives to achieving their stable employment and have therefore had to postpone their cohabitation and the arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on motherhood, although less influence on the time of starting cohabitation with a partner" explains Margarita Delgado, who is engaged in research in CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage and birth of offspring is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the degree of education, the higher the age when women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35 to 49 years, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child aged 25,1 or 32,1 respectively.
"There is another difference between women depending on their degree of education.
Women with primary education are getting married and giving birth to the first child before they find stable employment, while women with secondary or high education prefer to obtain stable employment, rather than marrying and having the first child," says Delgado.
